ding to tumor regression in two weeks and reopening of a collapsed lung: a case report. Clin Lung Cancer. Clin Lung Cancer. 2025;26:e126&#x2013;e129.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">39757042</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Jacobson C.A., Locke F.L., Ma L., et al. Real-world evidence of axicabtagene ciloleucel for the treatment of large B cell lymphoma in the United States. Transplant Cell Ther. 2022;28:581.e1&#x2013;581.e8.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC9427701</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">35609867</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Nastoupil L.J., JAin M.D., Feng L., et al. Standard-of-care axicabtagene ciloleucel for relapsed or refractory large B-cell lymphoma: results from the US lymphoma CAR T Consortium. J Clin Oncol. 2020;38:3119&#x2013;3128.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC7499611</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">32401634</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Riedell P.A., Hwang W.T., Nastoupil L.J., et al. Patterns of use outcomes, and resource utilization among recipients of commercial axicabtagene ciloleucel and tisagenlecleucel for relapsed/refractory aggressive B cell lymphomas. Transpl Cell Ther. 2022;28:669&#x2013;676.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC9547952</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">35850429</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41060525</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>14</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>14</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1865-8652</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>42</Volume><Issue>12</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Dec</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Advances in therapy</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Adv Ther</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Matching-Adjusted Indirect Treatment Comparison of Tarlatamab Versus Comparator Therapies in England in Patients with Extensive-Stage Small Cell Lung Cancer Who Have Received Two or More Prior Lines of Therapy.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>6078</StartPage><EndPage>6090</EndPage><MedlinePgn>6078-6090</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1007/s12325-025-03376-4</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="INTRODUCTION" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">The non-comparative phase&#xa0;2 DeLLphi-301 trial found that tarlatamab, a bispecific T&#xa0;cell engager immunotherapy, can provide sustained objective response rates and improved survival outcomes for patients with previously treated extensive-stage small cell lung cancer (ES-SCLC). In the absence of direct head-to-head evidence, an indirect treatment comparison was conducted to estimate the efficacy of tarlatamab relative to comparator therapies in England.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">The outcomes of patients in the DeLLphi-301 trial were compared against those of a comparator therapies cohort identified through linkage of population-level real-world databases in England. The study population consisted of patients with relapsed ES-SCLC who received two or more prior lines of therapy and who met key eligibility criteria from the DeLLphi-301 trial. Outcomes of interest included overall survival (OS) and progression-free survival (PFS). An unanchored matching-adjusted indirect comparison (MAIC) was used to estimate the efficacy of tarlatamab relative to available comparator therapies, adjusting for key baseline characteristics to match the patient cohort from DeLLphi-301 with the comparator therapies cohort. A weighted Cox proportional hazards model with robust variance estimation was used to estimate the hazard ratio (HR) and 95% confidence interval (CI) for both OS and PFS.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">The analyses included 97 patients enrolled in the DeLLphi-301 trial and 540 patients receiving available treatment options in England. After matching, tarlatamab was associated with improved OS (HR 0.24; 95%&#xa0;CI 0.14, 0.43) and PFS (HR 0.18; 95%&#xa0;CI 0.11, 0.31) relative to the comparator therapies. Findings were similar in sensitivity analyses performed by changing the variables for adjustment.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Tarlatamab provides a clinically meaningful survival benefit compared to currently available treatments in England. These findings support the use of tarlatamab as an effective treatment option for patients with previously treated ES-SCLC.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2025. The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer Healthcare Ltd., part of Springer Nature.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Takundwa</LastName><ForeName>Rumbidzai</ForeName><Initials>R</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Amgen Ltd., Uxbridge, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Suri</LastName><ForeName>Gaurav</ForeName><Initials>G</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Amgen Ltd., Uxbridge, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Dirnberger</LastName><ForeName>Franziska</ForeName><Initials>F</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Amgen GmbH, Munich, Germany.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Verhoek</LastName><ForeName>Andre</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Cytel, Rotterdam, Netherlands.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Vinand</LastName><ForeName>Elizabeth</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Cytel, London, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wang</LastName><ForeName>Jessie</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Amgen, Thousand Oaks, CA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Puntis</LastName><ForeName>Stephen</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Amgen Ltd., Uxbridge, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Pundole</LastName><ForeName>Xerxes</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Amgen, Thousand Oaks, CA, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Blackhall</LastName><ForeName>Fiona</ForeName><Initials>F</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Christie NHS Foundation Trust and University of Manchester, Wilmslow Road, Manchester, M20 4BX, UK. fiona.blackhall@nhs.net.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D003160">Comparative Study</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2025</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>08</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Adv Ther</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>8611864</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>0741-238X</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><MeshHeadingList><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D006801" MajorTopicYN="N">Humans</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D008175" MajorTopicYN="Y">Lung Neoplasms</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000188" MajorTopicYN="N">drug therapy</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000473" MajorTopicYN="N">pathology</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000401" MajorTopicYN="N">mortality</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D055752" MajorTopicYN="Y">Small Cell Lung Carcinoma</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000188" MajorTopicYN="N">drug therapy</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000473" MajorTopicYN="N">pathology</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000401" MajorTopicYN="N">mortality</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D008297" MajorTopicYN="N">Male</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D005260" MajorTopicYN="N">Female</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D004739" MajorTopicYN="N" Type="Geographic">England</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D000368" MajorTopicYN="N">Aged</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D008875" MajorTopicYN="N">Middle Aged</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D009367" MajorTopicYN="N">Neoplasm Staging</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D000369" MajorTopicYN="N">Aged, 80 and over</DescriptorName></MeshHeading></MeshHeadingList><OtherAbstract Type="plain-language-summary" Language="eng"><AbstractText>The phase&#xa0;2 non-comparative DeLLphi-301 trial demonstrated that tarlatamab, a bispecific T&#xa0;cell engager immunotherapy, can provide sustained objective response rates and improved survival outcomes for patients with previously treated extensive-stage small cell lung cancer. As a result of the lack of head-to-head comparison with current treatment options used in real-world clinical practice, this study aimed to ascertain the relative benefits of tarlatamab against current treatment options in England via a matching-adjusted indirect comparison. The overall survival and progression-free survival of 97 patients who received tarlatamab in the DeLLphi-301 trial were compared against that of 540 patients with extensive-stage small cell lung cancer in England and who met key eligibility criteria of the DeLLphi-301 trial. The findings of this matching-adjusted indirect comparison suggest that tarlatamab is associated with significant survival benefits relative to current treatment options in England. These results have the potential to enhance patient care by informing treatment decisions for patients with extensive-stage small cell lung cancer who have received two or more prior lines of therapy. In clinical practice, tarlatamab could emerge as a preferred treatment option, potentially influencing future treatment guidelines for extensive-stage small cell lung cancer.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2025. The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer Healthcare Ltd., part of Springer Nature.</CopyrightInformation></OtherAbstract><KeywordList Owner="NOTNLM"><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Comparative effectiveness</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Indirect treatment comparison</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Matching-adjusted indirect comparison</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Small cell lung cancer</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Survival</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Tarlatamab</Keyword></KeywordList><CoiStatement>Declarations. Conflict of Interests: Rumbidzai Takundwa, Jessie Wang, Stephen Puntis, Xerxes Pundole, and Franziska Dirnberger are employees of Amgen and hold stock/options. Gaurav Suri was an employee of Amgen at the time the study was conducted and holds stock/options. Andre Verhoek and Elizabeth Vinand are employees of Cytel which has received consulting fees from Amgen Inc. for the conduct of this research. Fiona Blackhall is funded by the National Institute for Health and Care Research (NIHR) Manchester Biomedical Research Centre (BRC) (NIHR203308) and reports personal fees for consulting from Amgen. Ethical Approval: Independent ethics committee approval was not required for this study because NCRAS has permission to record cancer data without patient consent under Section&#xa0;251 of the NHS Act 2006.</CoiStatement></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="received"><Year>2025</Year><Month>7</Month><Day>25</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="accepted"><Year>2025</Year><Month>9</Month><Day>10</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMed